<item>
            <title>[JDK-8306825] Monitor deflation might be accidentally disabled by zero intervals</title>
                <link>https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8306825</link>
                <project id="10100" key="JDK">JDK</project>
                    <description>Found this mistake while backporting &lt;a href=&quot;https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8305994&quot; title=&quot;Guarantee eventual async monitor deflation&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;JDK-8305994&quot;&gt;&lt;strike&gt;JDK-8305994&lt;/strike&gt;&lt;/a&gt;: if we put GADI=0 (defined as &amp;quot;disable guaranteed deflation&amp;quot;), then the MonitorDeflationThread would call `wait(0)`, that is, wait indefinitely for the notify. This breaks triggering the threshold heuristics! &lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
But what is even more concerning, the same thing would happen even prior to &lt;a href=&quot;https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-8305994&quot; title=&quot;Guarantee eventual async monitor deflation&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;JDK-8305994&quot;&gt;&lt;strike&gt;JDK-8305994&lt;/strike&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, if we put GuaranteedSafepointInterval=0 too. Which means users who kept GSI=0 as the way to dodge excess safepoints, now effectively disable monitor deflation.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Draft: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/13635&quot;&gt;https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/pull/13635&lt;/a&gt;</description>
